      "text": "<i>It might be an extreme form of [[Argument From Authority]]; then again appeals to \"most\" of anything seldom have anything resembling a survey of the group being referenced, in support of the proposition that \"most\" agree.  As a practical example, many commercials for medicine like to quote the omnipresent \"three out of four doctors\"--which often means \"three out of the four doctors who work for us that were asked the question\".  Proper citation from authority will reference actual studies or works published under the aegis of recognized scientific bodies*; not just drop the names of particular scientists or unverifieable samples of anonymous scientists.</i>",
